<br>
Kintire, while I agree wholeheartedly that in theory all the subdivisions of Christianity should agree on this subject, that just isn't true. Many people think differently from others, and because they place themselves in a bracket, doesn't mean they think the exact same as the people with them, just similarly. I guess what I'm saying is that site doesn't state the beliefs of all Christians. I know you don't believe that, so I'm just clarifying.<br>
<br>
I'm going to have to go with notwen, I like pie. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukambic.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kambic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/21/02 5:27:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseoutsidenorrath.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6324.topic&index=80>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://kambic.homestead.com/files/gate.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Creation vs Evolution</span><hr size=1> "Most notably, they all share a belief in the authority of the Bible, so any discussion on doctrines, like creationism, which is based on the bible can be addressed without reference to denomination. Not only that, but a lot of the stuff I quoted was referring to medieval beliefs.... we were all Catholic in those days. Well, in western europe we were anyway."<br>
<br>
As far as I am aware Catholics don't hold the Bible as sole authority - a lot of it is believed to be stories or metaphorical analogies. So to say that they believe the same was as the majority of protestants is incorrect.<br>
<br>
I don't really know what the point was for posting the account of creation... in makes perfect sense to me. Genesis 2 is a simple, but expanded, recounting of the 6th day of creation. God created even more animals (man was the only creature he only created 2 of... animals filled the earth) in Adam's presence. This is logical of God to do for several reasons, including to show Adam that, yes, He is the Creator, and also so that Satan couldn't come along later and say "Check out all this that I made, worhip me!"<br>
<br>
I'd also argue that it's assinine to say that the days could have been extended lengths of time. It's quite clear that God created the plants on the second day. Although God created light itself on the first day, he didn't create any heavenly bodies (most importantly the sun) until the 3rd day. Hope those plants were able to survive without light =(<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ukintire.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kintire</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/22/02 3:26:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseoutsidenorrath.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6324.topic&index=82>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Creation vs Evolution</span><hr size=1> 'Catholics don't hold the Bible as sole authority - a lot of it is believed to be stories or metaphorical analogies.'<br>
<br>
The Catholics don't hold the Bible as SOLE authority; they believe the writings of the saints were divinely inspired as well. They do believe in the authority of the Bible however. The differences between Catholics and protestants lie in the extra, over and above the bible bits, such as the authority of Priests and the various aspects of Mary worship.<br>
<br>
Of course, some Catholics do believe that there are a lot of metaphors in the Bible, as do some protestants, but it's not the mainstream view.<br>
<br>
'Genesis 2 is a simple, but expanded, recounting of the 6th day of creation. God created even more animals'<br>
 <br>
Back to that website again;<br>
<br>
'Let me give you [Genesis 2] verse 19: &quot;And out of the ground the LORD God formed every beast of the field, and every fowl of the air; and brought them unto Adam to see what he would call them: and whatsoever Adam called every living creature, that was the name thereof.&quot; <br>
<br>
Note: &quot;formed&quot;. Not &quot;had formed&quot;. It is interesting that, under pressure from creationists, many modern versions deliberately mistranslate this verse: without any warrant whatever from the Hebrew! What more proof could be needed that creationism is contrary to scripture, that it deliberately corrupts the very scripture it relies on?'<br>
<br>
Note also 'formed EVERY Beast.....EVERY fowl..'<br>
<br>
'I'd also argue that it's assinine to say that the days could have been extended lengths of time.'<br>
<br>
Why? That is what the Bible says; and that is also what the geologists and paleantologists say.  <br>
